# Coding Standards

Apply for implementation and refactors. Do X, avoid Y, verify with Z. Ref: [Cursor Rules](https://cursor.com/docs/context/rules). Complements `@architecture-and-design.mdc` (SOLID, clean arch, code smells).

## Core principle

Write code that is **readable before it is clever**. Prefer explicit over implicit.

## Formatting

- Use project formatter (e.g. Prettier, Black, Ruff). Run formatter before commit.
- Do not mix formatting-only changes with logic changes in one commit if the diff is large.

## Naming

- Consistent style per language (camelCase JS/TS, snake_case Python, etc.).
- Names must be **descriptive and intention-revealing**. No single-letter names except trivial loop indices.
- Types/interfaces: PascalCase. Constants: UPPER_SNAKE or camelCase by project.
- **Booleans** read as yes/no: `isLoading`, `hasPermission`, `canSubmit`.
- **Functions** are verbs: `fetchUser`, `validateInput`, `parseConfig`.
- Avoid abbreviations unless universally understood (`url`, `id`, `db`).

## Functions and methods

- Each function does **one thing** (Single Responsibility).
- Keep functions **under 30 lines**; extract if longer.
- **Prefer pure functions** with no side effects where possible.
- Limit parameters to **3 or fewer**; use an options/config object for more.
- Do not use output parameters; return values instead.
- Avoid flag arguments (`doSomething(true)`); split into two named functions.

## Module boundaries

- Prefer small, single-responsibility modules. Minimal public API (exports).
- Dependencies flow inward (domain < use cases < adapters). See `@architecture-and-design.mdc`.
- If you need "and" to describe a module, split it.

## Error handling

- **Never silently swallow errors** (no empty catch blocks).
- Log errors **with context** (what was attempted, relevant IDs).
- Use typed/named errors, not raw strings.
- Handle errors at the boundary closest to the user or caller.
- User-facing messages must not expose internals or stack traces. Validate inputs at boundaries.

## Logging

- Use a structured logger; no `console.log` in production paths.
- Levels: error (failures), warn (recoverable), info (notable events), debug (diagnostics).
- Never log secrets or PII in plain text.

## Comments

- Comments explain **why**, not **what**. The code explains itself.
- Do not add comments that restate the code.
- **Delete commented-out code** before committing. Delete dead code.
- TODO/FIXME: use sparingly; track in issues or backlog, not indefinitely in code.

## Dependencies and imports

- Keep imports organized; remove unused imports.
- Prefer well-maintained libraries over custom reimplementations.
- **Pin dependency versions** in production code.

## Testing

- Write tests for all non-trivial logic. Test **behavior**, not implementation details.
- Tests must be independent and deterministic (no shared mutable state between tests).
- Aim for meaningful coverage, not 100% line coverage.
- Name tests by behavior: `it('returns 401 when token is missing')`.
- Place tests next to source (`*.test.ts`) or in `test/`/`__tests__/` per project convention.

## TypeScript / Node defaults (optional)

- Use strict TypeScript; no `any` without a short comment justifying.
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes; `type` for unions/aliases. Export types that are public API.
- Prefer `const` and `readonly`; avoid mutable globals. `async/await` over raw Promises.

## Definition of Done (checklist)

Before marking a task or PR "done":

- [ ] Code follows formatting, naming, and function rules above.
- [ ] New behavior has tests (or explicitly excepted, e.g. spike).
- [ ] No new lint or type errors; `./scripts/verify.sh` passes.
- [ ] Errors and logging follow rules above.
- [ ] No secrets or credentials in code or logs.
- [ ] No code smells introduced (see `@architecture-and-design.mdc`).
- [ ] Public APIs documented or self-evident from names and types.

## When NOT to apply

- Prototype or spike code that will be discarded.
- Generated code (only ensure the generator config is under standards).
- Third-party or vendored code: do not modify style; only wrap or adapt.
